title: Centered colorings in minor-closed graph classes

sections.text:
#### Abstract

A vertex coloring $\varphi$ of a graph $G$ is $p$-centered if for every connected subgraph $H$ of $G$, either $\varphi$ uses more than $p$ colors on $H$, or there is a color that appears exactly once on $H$. We prove that for every fixed positive integer $t$, every $K_{t}$-minor-free graph admits a $p$-centered coloring using $\mathcal{O}\left(p^{t-1}\right)$ colors.

# 1. INTRODUCTION 

Let $G$ be a graph, $p$ be a positive integer, and $C$ be a set of colors. A coloring $\varphi: V(G) \rightarrow C$ of $G$ is $p$-centered if for every connected ${ }^{1}$ subgraph $H$ of $G$, either $\varphi$ uses more than $p$ colors on $H$, or there is a color that appears exactly once on $H$. The $p$-centered chromatic number of $G$, denoted by $\chi_{p}(G)$, introduced by Nešetřil and Ossona de Mendez [12], is the least nonnegative integer $k$ such that $G$ admits a $p$-centered coloring using $k$ colors. The following theorem is the main contribution of this paper.

Theorem 1. Let $t$ be an integer with $t \geqslant 2$. There exists an integer $c$ such that for every $K_{t}$-minor-free graph $G$ and for every positive integer $p$,

$$
\chi_{p}(G) \leqslant c \cdot p^{t-1}
$$

This improves on the work of Pilipczuk and Siebertz [14] who proved that for every integer $t$ with $t \geqslant 2, K_{t}$-minor-free graphs have $p$-centered chromatic number upper bounded by a polynomial in $p$. Contrary to Theorem 1, the degree of their polynomial is not explicitly given and arises from an application of the graph minor structure theorem by Robertson and Seymour [16]. On the other hand, Dębski, Micek, Schröder, and Felsner [5] showed that there exist $K_{t}$-minor-free graphs with $p$-centered chromatic number in $\Omega\left(p^{t-2}\right)$. Hence, Theorem 1 is tight, up to an $\mathcal{O}(p)$ factor. Let us provide some context for our theorem.

One of the driving forces in graph theory continues to be the development of efficient algorithms for computationally hard problems for sparse graph classes. Nešetřil and Ossona de Mendez [10] introduced the concepts of bounded expansion and nowhere denseness of classes of graphs. These notions cover many well-studied classes of graphs, such as planar graphs, graphs of bounded treewidth, graphs excluding a fixed minor, graphs of bounded book-thickness, or graphs that admit drawings with a bounded number of crossings per edge. See [11] by Nešetřil, Ossona de Mendez, and Wood, or the recent lecture notes [13] of Pilipczuk, Pilipczuk, and Siebertz. A key reason why centered colorings have gained significant attention is that they encapsulate the concept of bounded expansion. Indeed, a class of graphs $\mathcal{C}$ has bounded expansion if and only if there is a function $f: \mathbb{N} \rightarrow \mathbb{N}$ such that for all positive integers $p$, we have $\chi_{p}(G) \leqslant f(p)$ for every graph $G$ in $\mathcal{C}$, see again [10].

Centered colorings are also a crucial tool in designing parameterized algorithms in classes of graphs of bounded expansion. For example, Pilipczuk and Siebertz [14] showed that if $\mathcal{C}$ is a class of graphs excluding a fixed minor, then it can be decided whether a given $p$-vertex graph $H$ is a subgraph of a given $n$-vertex graph $G$ in $\mathcal{C}$ in time $2^{\mathcal{O}(p \log p)} \cdot n^{\mathcal{O}(1)}$ and space $n^{\mathcal{O}(1)}$. This algorithm relies on a general fact that the union of any $p$ color classes in a $p$-centered coloring induces a subgraph of treedepth at most $p$. Therefore, finding a $p$-centered coloring using $p^{\mathcal{O}(1)}$ colors, allows us to reduce the problem to graphs of bounded treedepth, on which the subgraph isomorphism problem can be solved efficiently. The running times of algorithms based on $p$-centered colorings heavily depend on the number of colors used.

Another important family of graph parameters capturing sparsity are the weak coloring numbers. Let $G$ be a graph, let $\sigma$ be a vertex ordering of $G$, and let $r$ be a nonnegative integer. For all $u$ and $v$ vertices of $G$, we say that $v$ is weakly $r$-reachable from $u$ in $(G, \sigma)$, if there exists a path between $u$ and $v$ in $G$ containing at most $r$ edges such that for every vertex $w$ on the path, $v \leqslant_{\sigma} w$. Let $\mathrm{WReach}_{r}[G, \sigma, u]$ be the set of all vertices that are weakly $r$-reachable

from $u$ in $(G, \sigma)$. The $r$-th weak coloring number of $G$ is defined as

$$
\operatorname{wcol}_{r}(G)=\min _{\sigma} \max _{u \in V(G)}\left|\operatorname{WReach}_{r}[G, \sigma, u]\right|
$$

where $\sigma$ ranges over all vertex orderings of $G$.
Van den Heuvel, Ossona de Mendez, Quiroz, Rabinovich, and Siebertz [8] established that for every integer $t$ with $t \geqslant 2$, for every $K_{t}$-minor-free graph $G$, we have $\operatorname{wcol}_{r}(G)=\mathcal{O}\left(r^{t-1}\right)$. Their proof hinges on a carefully designed partition of the vertex set of $G$, inspired by Andreae's work [1] on the cops and robber game for $K_{t}$-minor-free graphs. This partition, now commonly referred to as a chordal partition, mimics an elimination ordering of vertices of a chordal graph. Chordal partitions have since become a significant tool in both structural and algorithmic graph theory. In particular, $\operatorname{wcol}_{r}(G)=\mathcal{O}\left(r^{t-1}\right)$ is obtained in [8] with a relatively simple and selfcontained argument. However, there is currently no known analogous partitioning method that works well with $p$-centered colorings. In [14], the bound of $\chi_{p}(G)=\mathcal{O}\left(p^{g(t)}\right)$ for some function $g$ was achieved by first proving the result for graphs of bounded Euler genus, and then lifting the argument using the graph minor structure theorem by Robertson and Seymour [16]. The degree of the polynomial bound in $p$ they obtain depends on the constants of this structure theorem and is not explicitly given. Consequently, a significant gap exists between the state-of-art upper bounds for weak coloring numbers and the ones for centered chromatic numbers of $K_{t}$-minor-free graphs. In this work, we close this gap.

The main novelty of the proof is a replacement of a Helly-type property well-known for graphs of bounded treewidth (see Lemma 4) by a statement on centered colorings that works in the broader class of $K_{t}$-minor-free graphs. See the definition of $(p, c)$-good colorings and Lemma 5. The final centered colorings are constructed in this paper in two steps. First, we prove this Helly-type property for $K_{t}$-minor-free graphs following a layered variant of Robertson-Seymour decomposition introduced by Dujmović, Morin, and Wood [3] (see Theorem 6). Second, using this property, we adapt a framework proposed by Illingworth, Scott, and Wood in [9]. This in result allows us to move most of the dependency on $t$ from the degree of the final polynomial to a multiplicative constant in front of it. For a more detailed outline of the proof, see Section 2.

We remark that we also investigate bounds for $p$-centered chromatic numbers of $X$-minor-free graphs for an arbitrary fixed graph $X$. Theorem 1 implies an upper bound in $\mathcal{O}\left(p^{|V(X)|-1}\right)$. However, when $X$ is not a clique one might do much better. For instance, when $X$ has treedepth $t$, one can show that $\chi_{p}(G)$ for $X$-minor-free graphs $G$ is in $\mathcal{O}\left(p^{t-1} \log p\right)$. In particular, for any positive integers $s$ and $t$ with $s \leqslant t$, the maximum $p$-centered chromatic number of $K_{s, t^{-}}$ minor-free graphs is in $\mathcal{O}\left(p^{s} \log p\right)$. A manuscript detailing these results is being prepared.

Graphs with bounded degree have $p$-centered chromatic number in $\mathcal{O}(p)$ as proved in [5]. This, combined with the structure theorem by Grohe and Marx [7], gives a polynomial in $p$ upper bound on $\chi_{p}(G)$ for all $G$ excluding $K_{t}$ as a topological minor. However, the degree of this polynomial is not explicit. We conclude the introduction with the following problem suggestion.

Open problem. Let $t$ be an integer with $t \geqslant 2$. Does there exist a nonnegative integer $c$ such that, for every $K_{t}$-topological-minor-free graph $G$ and for every positive integer $p, \chi_{p}(G) \leqslant$ $c \cdot p^{t-1}$ ?

# 2. OUTLINE 

For a positive integer $k$, we write $[k]=\{1, \ldots, k\}$ and $[0]=\emptyset$. Let $S$ be a set. An ordering of a finite set $E$ is a sequence $\sigma=\left(x_{1}, \ldots, x_{|E|}\right)$ of all the elements of $E$. We write $\min _{\sigma} E=x_{1}$

and $\max _{\sigma} E=x_{|E|}$. A coloring of $S$ is a function $\varphi: S \rightarrow C$ for some set $C$. For each $u \in S$, we say that $\varphi(u)$ is the color of $u$ and subsequently we say that $\varphi(S)$ is the set of colors used by $\varphi$. For two colorings $\varphi_{1}$ and $\varphi_{2}$ of $S$, we define the coloring $\varphi_{1} \times \varphi_{2}$ of $S$, called the product coloring of $\varphi_{1}$ and $\varphi_{2}$, by $\left(\varphi_{1} \times \varphi_{2}\right)(u)=\left(\varphi_{1}(u), \varphi_{2}(u)\right)$ for every $u \in S$. Given $S^{\prime} \subseteq S$, an element $u \in S^{\prime}$ is a $\varphi$-center of $S^{\prime}$ if the color of $u$ is unique in $S^{\prime}$ under $\varphi$, in other words, $\varphi(u) \notin \varphi\left(S^{\prime}-\{u\}\right)$. Let $G$ be a graph. A coloring of $G$ is a coloring of $V(G)$. Recall that a coloring $\varphi$ of $G$ is a $p$-centered coloring of $G$ for a positive integer $p$ if for every connected subgraph $H$ of $G$, either $|\varphi(V(H))|>p$ or $V(H)$ has a $\varphi$-center. A collection $\mathcal{P}$ of subsets of a nonempty set $S$ is a partition of $S$ if elements of $\mathcal{P}$ are nonempty, pairwise disjoint, and $\bigcup \mathcal{P}=S$. Given a graph $G$ and a partition $\mathcal{P}$ of $V(G)$, the quotient graph $G / \mathcal{P}$ is the graph with the vertex set $\mathcal{P}$ and two distinct $P, P^{\prime} \in \mathcal{P}$ are adjacent in $G / \mathcal{P}$ if there are $u \in P$ and $u^{\prime} \in P^{\prime}$ such that $u u^{\prime}$ is an edge in $G$. The neighborhood of $u \in V(G)$ in a graph $G$, denoted by $N_{G}(u)$, is the set $\{v \in V(G) \mid u v \in E(G)\}$. For every set $X$ of vertices of a graph $G$, let $N_{G}(X)=\bigcup_{u \in X} N_{G}(u)-X$.

For a graph $H$, a model of $H$ in a graph $G$ is a family $\left(B_{x} \mid x \in V(H)\right)$ of disjoint subsets of $V(G)$ such that
(i) $G\left[B_{x}\right]$ is connected, for every $x \in V(H)$, and
(ii) there is an edge between $B_{x}$ and $B_{y}$ in $G$, for every $x y \in E(H)$.

If $G$ has a model of $H$, then we say that $H$ is a minor of $G$.
A tree decomposition of $G$ is a pair $\mathcal{W}=\left(T,\left(W_{x} \mid x \in V(T)\right)\right)$ where $T$ is a tree and $W_{x} \subseteq V(G)$ for every $x \in V(T)$ satisfying the following conditions:
(i) for every $u \in V(G), T\left[\left\{x \in V(T) \mid u \in W_{x}\right\}\right]$ is a connected subgraph of $T$, and
(ii) for every edge $u v \in E(G)$, there exists $x \in V(T)$ such that $u, v \in W_{x}$.

The sets $W_{x}$ are called the bags of $\mathcal{W}$. The sets $W_{x} \cap W_{y}$ for $x y \in E(T)$ are called the adhesions of $\mathcal{W}$. The width of $\mathcal{W}$ is $\max _{x \in V(T)}\left|W_{x}\right|-1$, and the treewidth of $G$, denoted by $\operatorname{tw}(G)$, is the minimum width of a tree decomposition of $G$. An elimination ordering of $\mathcal{W}^{i}$ is an ordering $\left(u_{1}, \ldots, u_{|V(G)|}\right)$ of $V(G)$ such that for every $i \in\|V(G)\|$, there exists $x \in V(T)$ such that

$$
\bigcup\left\{W_{z} \mid z \in V(T) \text { and } u_{i} \in W_{z}\right\} \cap\left\{u_{j} \mid j \in[i-1]\right\} \subseteq W_{x}
$$

Next, we explore the key ideas underlying the proof of Theorem 1.
First, let us discuss the centered colorings of graphs of bounded treewidth. Let $w$ and $t$ be positive integers with $t \geqslant 2$, and let $G$ be a graph with $\operatorname{tw}(G) \leqslant w$. Pilipczuk and Siebertz [14], showed that $\chi_{p}(G) \leqslant\binom{p+w}{w}=\mathcal{O}\left(p^{w}\right)$. In fact, they proved a stronger statement, namely, they used elimination orderings of tree decompositions to localize potential centers in a structured way. In order to state this stronger version of the result, let us define a variant of centered colorings in ordered graphs. Let $\sigma$ be an ordering of $V(G)$. A coloring $\varphi$ of $G$ is a $p$-centered coloring of $(G, \sigma)$ if for every connected subgraph $H$ of $G$, either $|\varphi(H)|>p$ or $\min _{\sigma} V(H)$ is a $\varphi$-center of $V(H)$. We denote by $\chi_{p}(G, \sigma)$ the least nonnegative integer $k$ such that $(G, \sigma)$ admits a $p$-centered coloring using $k$ colors.

Theorem 2 ([14]). Let $w$ be a positive integer, $G$ be a graph, and $\mathcal{W}$ be a tree decomposition of $G$ of width at most $w$. For every elimination ordering $\sigma$ of $\mathcal{W}$ and for every positive integer $p$,

$$
\chi_{p}(G, \sigma) \leqslant\binom{p+w}{w}
$$

The bound $\chi_{p}(G) \leqslant\binom{p+w}{w}$ for graphs with $\operatorname{tw}(G) \leqslant w$ can be used to obtain a good upper bound on the $p$-centered chromatic number of $K_{t}$-minor-free graphs of bounded treewidth. In an influential recent work, Illingworth, Scott, and Wood [9] proved that every $K_{t}$-minor-free graph $G$ with $\operatorname{tw}(G) \leqslant w$ admits a vertex-partition $\mathcal{P}$ such that $G / \mathcal{P}$ has treewidth at most $t-2$ and each part of $\mathcal{P}$ has at most $w+1$ elements ${ }^{3}$. This combined with Theorem 2 implies that for every $K_{t}$-minor-free graph $G$ of bounded treewidth, we have $\chi_{p}(G)=\mathcal{O}\left(p^{t-2}\right)$ as we show below. Let $G$ be a $K_{t}$-minor-free with $\operatorname{tw}(G) \leqslant w$ and let $\mathcal{P}$ be a partition of $V(G)$ as above. Let $\xi$ be a coloring of $G / \mathcal{P}$ given by Theorem 2 and $\rho$ be a coloring of $G$ using at most $w+1$ colors that is injective on each $P \in \mathcal{P}$. For every $P \in \mathcal{P}$ and $u \in P$, let $\zeta(u)=(\xi(P), \rho(u))$. To show that $\zeta$ is indeed a $p$-centered coloring of $G$, let $H$ be a connected subgraph of $G$ such that $|\zeta(V(H))| \leqslant p$. The parts of $\mathcal{P}$ that intersect $V(H)$ induce a connected subgraph of $G / \mathcal{P}$, thus, there is a $\xi$-center $P \in \mathcal{P}$ of the set of parts of $\mathcal{P}$ intersecting $V(H)$. Now, since $\rho$ is injective on $P$, any vertex in $P$ is a $\zeta$-center of $V(H)$.

The previous paragraph sketches the proof of the statement like in Theorem 1 but for $K_{t^{-}}$ minor-free graphs of bounded treewidth. The essential property of the parts in $\mathcal{P}$ we used is that their sizes are bounded. There is no hope of obtaining such a partition $\mathcal{P}$, with each part of size bounded by a constant, in the general case of $K_{t}$-minor-free graphs. This forces us to relax the condition on parts, so instead of bounding the maximal size of the part we want to maintain enough structural information. We accomplish this goal with an extra pre-coloring $\rho$ of vertices of $G$ so that we are able to mimic the proof as in the paragraph above. Since $\rho$ uses $\mathcal{O}(p)$ colors, this ultimately gives the bound $\mathcal{O}\left(p^{t-1}\right)$ instead of $\mathcal{O}\left(p^{t-2}\right)$. Below is a precise technical statement that we prove later in the paper and a simple argument that the statement together with Theorem 2 implies Theorem 1.

Lemma 3. For every positive integer $t$, there exists a positive integer $c_{3}(t)$ such that for every $K_{t}$-minor-free graph $G$ and every positive integer $p$, there exists a partition $\mathcal{P}$ of $V(G)$, a tree decomposition $\mathcal{W}$ of $G / \mathcal{P}$ of width at most $t-2$, an elimination ordering $\sigma=\left(P_{1}, \ldots, P_{t}\right)$ of $\mathcal{W}$, and a coloring $\rho$ of $G$ using at most $c_{3}(t) \cdot(p+1)$ colors such that for every connected subgraph $H$ of $G\left[\bigcup\left\{Q \in \mathcal{P} \mid Q \geqslant_{\sigma} P\right\}\right]$ with $V(H) \cap P \neq \emptyset$, either $|\rho(V(H))|>p$, or $V(H) \cap P$ has a $\rho$-center.

Proof of Theorem 1. Let $c_{3}(t)$ be the constant from Lemma 3, and let $c=2^{t-1} \cdot c_{3}(t)$. Let $G$ be a $K_{t}$-minor-free graph, and let $p$ be a positive integer. Let $\mathcal{P}, \mathcal{W}, \sigma$, and $\rho$ be obtained by Lemma 3. Let $\xi$ be a $p$-centered coloring of $G / \mathcal{P}$ using at most $\binom{p+t-2}{t-2}$ colors obtained from Theorem 2 applied to $G / \mathcal{P}, \mathcal{W}, \sigma$, and $p$. We define a coloring $\zeta$ of $G$ in the following way. For every $P \in \mathcal{P}$ and $u \in P$,

$$
\zeta(u)=(\xi(P), \rho(u))
$$

Note that

$$
|\zeta(V(G))| \leqslant\binom{p+t-2}{t-2} \cdot c_{3}(t) \cdot(p+1) \leqslant c_{3}(t) \cdot(p+1)^{t-1} \leqslant c \cdot p^{t-1}
$$

It remains to show that $\zeta$ is a $p$-centered coloring of $G$. Let $H$ be a connected subgraph of $G$ with $|\zeta(V(H))| \leqslant p$. Let $\mathcal{P}_{H}=\{P \in \mathcal{P} \mid P \cap V(H) \neq \emptyset\}$ and $P_{H}=\min _{\sigma} \mathcal{P}_{H}$. See Figure 1. Since $\left|\xi\left(\mathcal{P}_{H}\right)\right| \leqslant|\zeta(V(H))| \leqslant p$ and $\xi$ is a $p$-centered coloring of $(G / \mathcal{P}, \sigma), P_{H}$ is a $\xi$-center of $\mathcal{P}_{H}$. So $\zeta(u) \neq \zeta(v)$ for all $u \in V(H) \cap P_{H}$ and $v \in V(H)-P_{H}$. Now, $H$ is a connected subgraph of $G\left[\bigcup\left\{Q \in \mathcal{P} \mid Q \geqslant_{\sigma} P_{H}\right\}\right]$ with $V(H) \cap P_{H} \neq \emptyset$ by definition of $P_{H}$. Since $|\rho(V(H))| \leqslant|\zeta(V(H))| \leqslant p$, there exists a $\rho$-center $u$ in $V(H) \cap P_{H}$. It follows that $u$ is a $\zeta$-center in $V(H)$. We conclude that $\zeta$ is indeed a $p$-centered coloring of $G$.

The proof of Lemma 3 draws on the ideas from [9]. Let $t$ be an integer with $t \geqslant 2$, and let $G$ be a $K_{t}$-minor-free graph. Next, we describe a key step of the construction (from [9]) of a partition $\mathcal{P}$ of vertices of $G$ such that $G / \mathcal{P}$ has treewidth at most $t-2$ and each part of $\mathcal{P}$ has at most $\operatorname{tw}(G)+1$ elements. Let $R=\left\{r_{1}, \ldots, r_{t-2}\right\}$ be a subset of vertices of $G$. (One can think of vertices in $R$ as contracted parts of the vertex-partition constructed so far.) For simplicity, assume that $G-R$ is connected. Set $\mathcal{F}$ to be the family of all connected subgraphs of $G-R$ adjacent to all $r_{1}, \ldots, r_{t-2}$ in $G$. Since $G$ is $K_{t}$-minor-free (and $G-R$ is connected), $\mathcal{F}$ does not contain $t$ pairwise disjoint members, as otherwise, $G$ contains a $K_{t}$-minor (as shown in Figure 3). Now comes the critical moment when the argument (from [9]) exploits the fact that $G$ has bounded treewidth and therefore $G$ admits the following Helly-type property.

Lemma 4 ([15, Statement (8.7)]). For every graph $G$, for every tree decomposition $\mathcal{V}$ of $G$, for every family $\mathcal{F}$ of connected subgraphs of $G$, for every nonnegative integer $d$, either
(i) there are $d+1$ pairwise vertex-disjoint subgraphs in $\mathcal{F}$, or
(ii) there is a set $Z$ that is the union of at most $d$ bags of $\mathcal{V}$ such that $V(F) \cap Z \neq \emptyset$ for every $F \in \mathcal{F}$.

We take as $\mathcal{V}$ a tree decomposition of $G$ witnessing treewidth of $G$ and now Lemma 4 implies that there is a set $Z \subseteq V(G)$ of size at most $t \cdot(\operatorname{tw}(G)+1)$ such that $V(F) \cap Z \neq \emptyset$ for every $F \in \mathcal{F}$. This set $Z$ is destined to be a new part in the constructed vertex-partition. The key property is that each component $C$ of $G-R-Z$ is not in $\mathcal{F}$, and so $C$ is not adjacent to at least one vertex in $R$. This allows us to continue the process for $C$ where a non-adjacent to $C$ vertex of $R$ is replaced by the contraction of $Z$. This sketch omits numerous details, e.g. we do not know if $Z$ is connected in $G$.

The key property of a graph $G$ required for the idea in [9] to work is that for every family $\mathcal{F}$ of connected subgraphs of $G$, there is a hitting set ${ }^{4}$ of $\mathcal{F}$ of size bounded by a function of the packing number ${ }^{5}$ of $\mathcal{F}$. Graphs of bounded treewidth indeed satisfy this property as witnessed by Lemma 4. However, $K_{t}$-minor-free graphs do not admit such a Helly-type property ${ }^{6}$. The observation that will eventually lead to the proof of Theorem 1 is that we do not need these hitting sets to have bounded size, as long as we can find a suitable coloring for them.

More precisely, we propose the following technical definition. Let $p$ and $c$ be positive integers. A coloring $\varphi$ of $G$ is $(p, c)$-good if for every subgraph $G_{0}$ of $G$, for every family $\mathcal{F}$ of connected

(pc1) $V(F) \cap Z \neq \emptyset$ for every $F \in \mathcal{F}$;

(pc3) for every component $C$ of $G_{0}-Z, N_{G_{0}}(V(C))$ intersects at most two components of $G_{0}-V(C)$.
The main technical step of our proof is the following lemma proved in Section 5.
Lemma 5. For every positive integer $t$, there exists a positive integer $c_{5}(t)$ such that for every $K_{t}$-minor-free graph $G$ and every positive integer $p, G$ admits a $\left(p, c_{5}(t)\right)$-good coloring using $p+1$ colors.

The existence of good colorings in $K_{t}$-minor-free graphs (Lemma 5) suffices to replace the role of Lemma 4 in the sketched proof framework of [9] and this way we close the proof of Lemma 3. See Section 4.

In the remainder of the section, we discuss the ideas behind the proof of Lemma 5. For simplicity, in this outline, we consider a simpler variant of good colorings, where we drop (pc3). Observe that in the definition of good colorings, a subgraph $G_{0}$ occurs only in (pc3), hence, if we ignore this item, we can also assume that $G_{0}=G$. Solely for this outline, we say that a coloring is a simple $(p, c)$-good coloring if it admits the relaxed definition as discussed above.

For graphs of bounded treewidth, there is a straightforward way of constructing simple good colorings. Let $G$ be a graph. We can set $\varphi$ to use only one color, and for a family $\mathcal{F}$ of connected subgraphs of $G$ having no $d+1$ pairwise disjoint members we take $Z$ as given by Lemma 4, so (pc1) is satisfied. For an injective $\psi: Z \rightarrow[(\operatorname{tw}(G)+1) \cdot d]$, (pc2) is clearly satisfied. This gives a $\left(p, \operatorname{tw}(G)+1\right)$-good coloring of $G$ using one color for every positive integer $p$. A true inspiration for the definition of good colorings comes from the case of graphs of bounded layered treewidth. Let us first introduce this parameter properly.

A layered tree decomposition of $G$ is a pair $(\mathcal{W}, \mathcal{L})$ where $\mathcal{W}=\left(T,\left(W_{x} \mid x \in V(T)\right)\right)$ is a tree decomposition of $G$, and $\mathcal{L}=\left(L_{i} \mid i \in \mathbb{N}\right)^{7}$ is a layering of $G$, that is, a family of pairwise disjoint subsets of $V(G)$ whose union is $V(G)$ and such that for every edge $u v$ of $G$, there exists $i \in \mathbb{N}$ such that $u, v \in L_{i} \cup L_{i+1}$. The width of $(\mathcal{W}, \mathcal{L})$ is $\max \left|W_{x} \cap L_{i}\right|$ over all $x \in V(T)$ and $i \in \mathbb{N}$. The layered treewidth of $G$, denoted by $\operatorname{ltw}(G)$, is the minimum width of a layered tree decomposition of $G$.

A typical example of a family of graphs of bounded layered treewidth but unbounded treewidth is the family of planar graphs. Indeed, building upon ideas by Eppstein [6], Dujmović, Morin, and Wood [4] proved that planar graphs have layered treewidth at most three.

Let $T$ be a tree rooted in a vertex $r$. For every vertex $v$ of $T$ with $v \neq r$, we define $\mathrm{p}(T, v)$ to be the vertex following $v$ on the path from $v$ to $r$ in $T$. For a subtree $T^{\prime}$ of $T$, we define $\operatorname{root}\left(T^{\prime}\right)$ as the unique vertex in $T^{\prime}$ closest to $r$ in $T$.

Let $u, v$ be two (not necessarily distinct) vertices of $T$. The lowest common ancestor of $u$ and $v$ in $T$, denoted by $\operatorname{lca}(T, u, v)$, is the furthest vertex from the root that has $u$ and $v$ as descendants. Let $Y \subseteq V(T)$. The lowest common ancestor closure of $Y$ in $T$ is the set $\operatorname{LCA}(T, Y)=\{\operatorname{lca}(T, u, v) \mid u, v \in Y\}$. Lemma 10. Let $G$ be a graph, and let $W \subseteq V(G)$. If $H$ is a connected subgraph of $G$ intersecting $W$, then $V(H) \cap W$ induces a connected subgraph of $\operatorname{torso}_{G}(W)$.

Proof. Let $H$ be a connected subgraph of $G$ intersecting $W$, and suppose to the contrary that the subgraph $H_{W}$ of $\operatorname{torso}_{G}(W)$ induced by $V(H) \cap W$ is not connected. It follows that $u$ and $v$ are adjacent in $\operatorname{torso}_{G}(W)$, and so, in $H_{W}$, which contradicts the assumption and completes the proof.

# 5. CONSTRUCTING GOOD COLORINGS 

In this section, we prove Lemma 5, namely, we show that for every positive integer $t$, there exists a positive integer $c_{5}(t)$ such that for every $K_{t}$-minor-free graph $G$ and every positive integer $p, G$ admits a $\left(p, c_{5}(t)\right)$-good coloring using $p+1$ colors.

At one point in the proof, we would like to assume that the tree decomposition that we consider is natural but still preserves certain properties. For this reason, we introduce the following definitions and we prove Lemma 12.

Let $G$ be a graph. A pair $(\mathcal{U}, \mathcal{P})$ is a normal pair of $G$ if $\mathcal{U}=\left(T,\left(U_{t} \mid t \in V(T)\right)\right)$ is a tree decomposition of $G$, and $\mathcal{P}$ is a collection of connected subgraphs of $T$ whose vertex sets partition $V(T)$. Consider two normal pairs $(\mathcal{U}, \mathcal{P})$ and $(\mathcal{V}, \mathcal{Q})$ of $G$ with $\mathcal{U}=\left(T,\left(U_{t} \mid t \in\right.\right.$ $V(T)))$ and $\mathcal{V}=\left(S,\left(V_{s} \mid s \in V(S)\right)\right)$. We say that $(\mathcal{V}, \mathcal{Q})$ refines, or is a refinement of $(\mathcal{U}, \mathcal{P})$ if there exist $f: V(S) \rightarrow V(T)$ and $g: \mathcal{Q} \rightarrow \mathcal{P}$ such that
(r1) for every $s \in V(S)$,

$$
V_{s} \subseteq U_{f(s)}
$$

(r2) for every $Q \in \mathcal{Q}$,

$$
f(V(Q)) \subseteq V(g(Q))
$$

However, this contradicts the minimality of $|\mathcal{Q}|$. We obtain that indeed $g(Q) \neq g\left(Q^{\prime}\right)$, and so, $x(Q) \neq x\left(Q^{\prime}\right)$. In particular,

$$
\left|V_{y} \cap V_{z}\right| \leqslant\left|U_{(x(Q), f(y))} \cap U_{\left(x\left(Q^{\prime}\right), f\left(y^{\prime}\right)\right)}\right| \leqslant\left|W_{x(Q)} \cap W_{x\left(Q^{\prime}\right)}\right| \leqslant c_{0}(t)
$$

where the first inequality follows from (r1), the second from the properties of tree decompositions, and the last from (lrs1).

Claim 14. Let $x \in V(T), y \in V(S)$, and $i \in \mathbb{N}$. Then

$$
\left|V_{y} \cap L_{x, i}\right| \leqslant c_{0}(t)
$$

Proof of Claim 14. Since $(\mathcal{V}, \mathcal{Q})$ refines $(\mathcal{U}, \mathcal{P})$ we have that $V_{y} \subseteq U_{f(y)}$. Let $f(y)=\left(x^{\prime}, z\right)$ where $x^{\prime} \in V(T)$ and $z \in V\left(T_{x^{\prime}}\right)$. Thus, $U_{f(y)}=U_{\left(x^{\prime}, z\right)}=\left(D_{x^{\prime}, z} \cup A_{x^{\prime}}\right) \cap V\left(G_{0}\right)$. Recall that $A_{x} \cap L_{x, i}=\emptyset$. Thus in the case of $x=x^{\prime}$,

$$
\left|V_{y} \cap L_{x, i}\right| \leqslant\left|U_{(x, z)} \cap L_{x, i}\right| \leqslant\left|\left(D_{x, z} \cup A_{x}\right) \cap L_{x, i}\right| \leqslant\left|D_{x, z} \cap L_{x, i}\right| \leqslant c_{0}(t)
$$

where the last inequality follows by (lrs5). Finally, in the case of $x \neq x^{\prime}$, we have $U_{\left(x^{\prime}, z\right)} \subseteq W_{x^{\prime}}$ and $L_{x, i} \subseteq W_{x}$, and so,

$$
\left|V_{y} \cap L_{x, i}\right| \leqslant\left|U_{\left(x^{\prime}, z\right)} \cap L_{x, i}\right| \leqslant\left|W_{x^{\prime}} \cap W_{x}\right| \leqslant c_{0}(t)
$$

![img-8.jpeg](img-8.jpeg)

Figure 9. Here, $V=\left\{v_{1}, v_{2}, v_{3}, v_{4}\right\}$. Note that $\bigcup_{y \in V(Q)} V_{y}$ is separated from $V$ by $\Pi(Q, V)$ in $G_{0}$ as we show later in Claim 15.
where the last inequality follows from (lrs1).

We root $S$ in an arbitrary vertex $\operatorname{root}(S)$. For every $X \subseteq V(S)$, we define

$$
\mathcal{Q}(X)=\{Q \in \mathcal{Q} \mid V(Q) \cap X \neq \emptyset\}
$$

Let $d$ be a positive integer, and let $\mathcal{F}$ be a family of connected subgraphs of $G_{0}$ such that there are no $d+1$ pairwise disjoint members of $\mathcal{F}$. In the remainder of the proof, we construct $Z$ and $\psi$ satisfying (pc1)-(pc3).

By Lemma 4, there exists $X_{0} \subseteq V(S)$ of size at most $d$ such that $\bigcup_{y \in X_{0}} V_{y}$ intersects every member of $\mathcal{F}$. Let

$$
X_{1}=\operatorname{LCA}\left(S, X_{0}\right)
$$

By Lemma 7,

$$
\left|\mathcal{Q}\left(X_{1}\right)\right| \leqslant\left|X_{1}\right| \leqslant 2 d-1
$$

The set $\bigcup_{y \in X_{1}} V_{y}$ is a hitting set of $\mathcal{F}$, thus, it is a good candidate to be $Z$. However, we still need to define $\psi$ and the ultimate goal is to repeat the idea of coloring that we applied in the bounded layered treewidth case. Since $\mathcal{L}_{x}$ is a layering of torso $_{G}\left(W_{x}\right)-A_{x}$, we need to take into account the vertices in $A_{x}$ when building the final $Z$. Moreover, the coloring $\varphi$ may not be compatible with layerings on the adhesions of $\mathcal{W}$, we also need to consider some of them. To this end, we will add some more vertices to $Z$, which we ultimately color injectively with a separate palette of colors. Because we work with $\mathcal{V}$ instead of $\mathcal{U}$ we need the following notions of projections. See also Figure 9 for an illustration.

Let $Q \in \mathcal{Q}$ and $v \in V\left(G_{0}\right)$. Let $S_{v}=S\left[\left\{z \in V(S) \mid v \in V_{z}\right\}\right]$. Thus, $Q$ and $S_{v}$ are two subtrees of $S$. We define projections $\pi(Q, v)$ and $\Pi(Q, v)$ as follows. If $Q$ and $S_{v}$ share a vertex, then choose such a vertex $z$ arbitrarily and set $\pi(Q, v)=z$ and $\Pi(Q, v)=\{v\}$. If $V(Q)$ and $V\left(S_{v}\right)$ are disjoint, then consider the shortest path in $S$ between $V(Q)$ and $V\left(S_{v}\right)$. Let $z$ be the endpoint of that path in $Q$ and $y$ be the vertex adjacent to $z$ in that path. Then set $\pi(Q, v)=z$ and $\Pi(Q, v)=V_{y} \cap V_{z}$. The definition can be naturally extended to subsets of $V\left(G_{0}\right)$. For each $V \subseteq V\left(G_{0}\right)$, let

$$
\pi(Q, V)=\{\pi(Q, v) \mid v \in V\} \text { and } \Pi(Q, V)=\bigcup_{v \in V} \Pi(Q, v)
$$

Note that by Claim 13,

$$
|\Pi(Q, V)| \leqslant c_{0}(t) \cdot|V|
$$

The key property of these objects is the following. See Figure 9 again.
Claim 15. Let $Q \in \mathcal{Q}$ and $V \subseteq V\left(G_{0}\right)$. Every connected subgraph $H$ of $G_{0}-\Pi(Q, V)$ that intersects $\bigcup_{y \in V(Q)} V_{y}$ is disjoint from $V$.

Proof. It suffices to observe that by the properties of tree decompositions and construction, $\Pi(Q, V)$ intersects every path between $\bigcup_{y \in V(Q)} V_{y}$ and $V$ in $G_{0}$. Thus, if a connected subgraph $H$ of $G_{0}$ has a vertex is both $\bigcup_{y \in V(Q)} V_{y}$ and $V$, then it has a vertex in $\Pi(Q, V)$.

Let

$$
Y_{Q}= \begin{cases}\pi(Q, A_{x(Q)}) & \text { if } x(Q)=r \\ \pi\left(Q, A_{x(Q)} \cup\left(W_{x(Q)} \cap W_{\mathrm{p}(T, x(Q))}\right)\right) & \text { if } x(Q) \neq r\end{cases}
$$

Recall that $\left|A_{x(Q)}\right| \leqslant c_{0}(t)$ by (lrs2), and if $x(Q) \neq r$, then $\left|W_{x(Q)} \cap W_{\mathrm{p}(T, x(Q))}\right| \leqslant c_{0}(t)$ by (lrs1). Thus, we have

$$
\begin{array}{ll}
\left|Y_{Q}\right| \leqslant\left|A_{x(Q)}\right| & \leqslant c_{0}(t) \quad \text { if } x(Q)=r \\
\left|Y_{Q}\right| \leqslant\left|A_{x(Q)}\right|+\left|W_{x(Q)} \cap W_{\mathrm{p}(T, x(Q))}\right| & \leqslant 2 c_{0}(t) \quad \text { if } x(Q) \neq r
\end{array}
$$

Moreover, by definition $Y_{Q} \subseteq V(Q)$.
Let

$$
X_{2}=X_{1} \cup\left\{\operatorname{root}(Q) \mid Q \in \mathcal{Q}\left(X_{1}\right)\right\} \cup \bigcup\left\{Y_{Q} \mid Q \in \mathcal{Q}\left(X_{1}\right)\right\}
$$

and

$$
X_{3}=\operatorname{LCA}\left(S, X_{2}\right)
$$

Observe that

$$
\begin{aligned}
\left|X_{3}\right| & \leqslant 2\left|X_{2}\right|-1 & & \text { by Lemma } 7 \\
& \leqslant 2\left(\left|X_{1}\right|+\left|\mathcal{Q}\left(X_{1}\right)\right|+\left|\mathcal{Q}\left(X_{1}\right)\right| \cdot 2 c_{0}(t)\right)-1 & & \text { by (3) } \\
& \leqslant 2((2 d-1)+(2 d-1)+\left.(2 d-1) \cdot 2 c_{0}(t)\right)-1 & & \text { by (1) } \\
& \leqslant\left(8 c_{0}(t)+8\right) d .
\end{aligned}
$$

Recall that by Lemma 9, for all $X, Y \subseteq V(S)$ with $X \subseteq Y$ and $\operatorname{LCA}(S, X)=X$, if $\mathcal{Q}(X)=$ $\mathcal{Q}(Y)$, then $\mathcal{Q}(Y)=\mathcal{Q}(\operatorname{LCA}(S, Y))$. Since by construction $\mathcal{Q}\left(X_{1}\right)=\mathcal{Q}\left(X_{2}\right)$, we can apply the above with $X=X_{1}$ and $Y=X_{2}$ to obtain that

$$
\mathcal{Q}\left(X_{1}\right)=\mathcal{Q}\left(X_{2}\right)=\mathcal{Q}\left(X_{3}\right)
$$

Finally, the set $Z$ that witnesses the assertion of the claim is given by

$$
Z=\bigcup_{y \in X_{3}} V_{y}
$$

Next, consider $Q \in \mathcal{Q}\left(X_{1}\right)$, and let

$$
B_{Q}= \begin{cases}\Pi\left(Q, A_{x(Q)}\right) & \text { if } x(Q)=r \\ \Pi\left(Q, A_{x(Q)} \cup\left(W_{x(Q)} \cap W_{\mathrm{p}(T, x(Q))}\right)\right) & \text { if } x(Q) \neq r\end{cases}
$$

Since for every $v \in V\left(G_{0}\right), \Pi(Q, v) \subseteq V_{\pi(Q, v)}$ and $Y_{Q} \subseteq X_{2} \subseteq X_{3}$, we have

$$
B_{Q} \subseteq \bigcup_{y \in Y_{Q}} V_{y} \subseteq \bigcup_{y \in X_{2}} V_{y} \subseteq Z
$$

Recall that $\left|A_{x(Q)}\right| \leqslant c_{0}(t)$ by (lrs2), and if $x(Q) \neq r$, then $\left|W_{x(Q)} \cap W_{\mathrm{p}(T, x(Q))}\right| \leqslant c_{0}(t)$ by (lrs1). Thus, by (2), we have

$$
\begin{array}{ll}
\left|B_{Q}\right| \leqslant\left|A_{x(Q)}\right| \cdot c_{0}(t) & \leqslant\left(c_{0}(t)\right)^{2} \quad \text { if } x(Q)=r \\
\left|B_{Q}\right| \leqslant\left|A_{x(Q)} \cup\left(W_{x(Q)} \cap W_{\mathrm{p}(T, x(Q))}\right)\right| \cdot c_{0}(t) & \leqslant 2\left(c_{0}(t)\right)^{2} \quad \text { if } x(Q) \neq r
\end{array}
$$

Let

$$
B=\left(\bigcup_{Q \in \mathcal{Q}\left(X_{1}\right), \operatorname{root}(S) \notin V(Q)} V_{\operatorname{root}(Q)} \cap V_{\mathrm{p}(S, \operatorname{root}(Q))}\right) \cup\left(\bigcup_{Q \in \mathcal{Q}\left(X_{1}\right)} B_{Q}\right)
$$

Recall that for every $Q \in \mathcal{Q}\left(X_{1}\right)$ with $\operatorname{root}(S) \notin V(Q), \operatorname{root}(Q) \in X_{2}$ and so $V_{\operatorname{root}(Q)} \cap$ $V_{\mathrm{p}(S, \operatorname{root}(Q))} \subseteq V_{\operatorname{root}(Q)} \subseteq Z$. Moreover, for every $Q \in \mathcal{Q}\left(X_{1}\right), B_{Q} \subseteq Z$. Therefore,

$$
B \subseteq Z
$$

Observe also that

$$
\begin{aligned}
|B| & \leqslant\left|\mathcal{Q}\left(X_{1}\right)\right| \cdot c_{0}(t)+\left|\mathcal{Q}\left(X_{1}\right)\right| \cdot 2\left(c_{0}(t)\right)^{2} \quad \text { by Claim 13 and (5) } \\
& \leqslant(2 d-1) \cdot c_{0}(t)+(2 d-1) \cdot 2\left(c_{0}(t)\right)^{2} \quad \text { by (1) } \\
& \leqslant c_{0}(t)\left(4 c_{0}(t)+2\right) d
\end{aligned}
$$

Claim 16. For all distinct $Q_{1}, Q_{2} \in \mathcal{Q}\left(X_{1}\right)$, there is no path between $\bigcup_{y \in V\left(Q_{1}\right)} V_{y}-B$ and $\bigcup_{y \in V\left(Q_{2}\right)} V_{y}-B$ in $G_{0}-B$. In particular, $\bigcup_{y \in V\left(Q_{1}\right)} V_{y}-B$ and $\bigcup_{y \in V\left(Q_{2}\right)} V_{y}-B$ are disjoint.

Proof of Claim 16. Let $Q_{1}, Q_{2}$ be distinct members of $\mathcal{Q}\left(X_{1}\right)$. Recall that $Q_{1}, Q_{2}$ are disjoint subtrees of $S$. Note that there exists $i \in\{1,2\}$ such that $\operatorname{root}\left(Q_{i}\right) \neq \operatorname{root}(S)$ and every path in $S$ between $Q_{1}$ and $Q_{2}$ goes through the edge $\operatorname{root}\left(Q_{i}\right) \mathrm{p}\left(S, \operatorname{root}\left(Q_{i}\right)\right)$ of $S$. Hence by properties of tree decompositions, $V_{\operatorname{root}\left(Q_{i}\right)} \cap V_{\mathrm{p}\left(S, \operatorname{root}\left(Q_{i}\right)\right)}$ intersects every path between $\bigcup_{y \in V\left(Q_{1}\right)} V_{y}$ and $\bigcup_{y \in V\left(Q_{2}\right)} V_{y}$ in $G_{0}$. Since $V_{\operatorname{root}\left(Q_{i}\right)} \cap V_{\mathrm{p}\left(S, \operatorname{root}\left(Q_{i}\right)\right)} \subseteq B$, this proves the claim.

As a consequence of Claim 16, $\left\{\left(\bigcup_{y \in V(Q)} V_{y}\right) \cap(Z-B) \mid Q \in \mathcal{Q}\left(X_{1}\right)\right\}$ is a family of pairwise disjoint sets covering $Z-B$ (because $\mathcal{Q}\left(X_{1}\right)=\mathcal{Q}\left(X_{3}\right)$ ). We want to refine this family with the layerings of the torsos. To this end, we need the following fact where we substantially use the fact that $(\mathcal{V}, \mathcal{Q})$ refines $(\mathcal{U}, \mathcal{P})$.

Claim 17. For every $Q \in \mathcal{Q}\left(X_{1}\right)$ and $V \subseteq V\left(G_{0}\right)$ such that $\Pi(Q, V) \subseteq B_{Q}$, we have

$$
\bigcup_{y \in V(Q)} V_{y}-B \subseteq W_{x(Q)}-V
$$

Proof of Claim 17. Let $Q \in \mathcal{Q}\left(X_{1}\right)$ and let $V \subseteq V\left(G_{0}\right)$ be such that $\Pi(Q, V) \subseteq B_{Q}$. Since $\Pi(Q, V) \subseteq B_{Q} \subseteq B$, then

$$
\bigcup_{y \in V(Q)} V_{y}-B \subseteq \bigcup_{y \in V(Q)} V_{y}-B_{Q} \subseteq \bigcup_{y \in V(Q)} V_{y}-\Pi(Q, V)
$$

By Claim 15, $\bigcup_{y \in V(Q)} V_{y}-\Pi(Q, V)$ is disjoint from $V$. Thus, to conclude the claim, it suffices to show that $\bigcup_{y \in V(Q)} V_{y} \subseteq W_{x(Q)}$. Recall that $g(Q)=T_{0}\left[\{x(Q)\} \times T_{x(Q)}\right]$. We have

$$
\bigcup_{y \in V(Q)} V_{y} \subseteq \bigcup_{y \in V(Q)} U_{f(y)} \subseteq \bigcup_{z \in V(g(Q))} U_{z}=\bigcup_{z \in\{x(Q)\} \times T_{x(Q)}} U_{z} \subseteq W_{x(Q)}
$$

where the first inclusion follows from (r1), the second from (r2), and the last one from the construction of $\mathcal{U}$.

![img-9.jpeg](img-9.jpeg)

Figure 10. The set $Z$ is the union of $B$ and the members of $\mathcal{B}$. We color the vertices in $B$ injectively. The role of the set $B$ is to separate members of $\mathcal{B}$ so that if $B$ is intersected by a connected subgraph $H$ of $G_{0}$, then we immediately get a center. In the figure, $B_{1}=\bigcup_{y \in V\left(Q_{1}\right)} V_{y}-B$ and $B_{2}=\bigcup_{y \in V\left(Q_{2}\right)} V_{y}-B$ for some $Q_{1}, Q_{2} \in \mathcal{Q}\left(X_{3}\right)$. If a connected subgraph $H$ of $G_{0}$, intersects both $B_{1}$ and $B_{2}$, then it has to intersect $B$.

Since $\Pi\left(Q, A_{x(Q)}\right) \subseteq B_{Q}$ for every $Q \in \mathcal{Q}\left(X_{1}\right)$, by Claim 17,

$$
\left(\bigcup_{y \in V(Q)} V_{y}-B\right) \cap A_{x(Q)}=\emptyset
$$

Recall that for every $Q \in \mathcal{Q}\left(X_{1}\right),\left(L_{x(Q), i} \mid i \in \mathbb{N}\right)$ is a layering of $\operatorname{torso}_{G}\left(W_{x(Q)}\right)-A_{x(Q)}$. It follows that the family

$$
\mathcal{B}=\left\{\left(\bigcup_{y \in V(Q)} V_{y}\right) \cap L_{x(Q), i} \cap(Z-B) \mid Q \in \mathcal{Q}\left(X_{1}\right), i \in \mathbb{N}\right\}
$$

is a family of pairwise disjoint sets covering $Z-B$. Moreover, the members of $\mathcal{B}$ are of reasonable size, namely, for every $Q \in \mathcal{Q}\left(X_{1}\right)$ and $i \in \mathbb{N}$,

$$
\begin{aligned}
\left|\left(\bigcup_{y \in V(Q)} V_{y}\right) \cap L_{x(Q), i} \cap(Z-B)\right| & \leqslant\left|L_{x(Q), i} \cap Z\right| \leqslant \sum_{y \in X_{3}}\left|L_{x(Q), i} \cap V_{y}\right| \\
& \leqslant \sum_{y \in X_{3}}\left|L_{x(Q), i} \cap U_{f(y)}\right| \\
& \leqslant c_{\mathrm{c}}(t) \cdot\left|X_{3}\right| \\
& \leqslant c_{\mathrm{c}}(t) \cdot\left(8 c_{\mathrm{c}}(t)+8\right) d
\end{aligned}
$$

by (r1)
by (r1)
by (4).

We define a coloring $\psi$ of $Z$ using at most $c_{\mathrm{c}}(t)$ colors. See also Figure 10. First, we color $B$ injectively, and then we color each member of $\mathcal{B}$ also injectively avoiding colors in $\psi(B)$. In the first step we used at most $c_{\mathrm{c}}(t)\left(4 c_{\mathrm{c}}(t)+2\right) d$ colors by (6), and in the second step, we used at most $c_{\mathrm{c}}(t) \cdot\left(8 c_{\mathrm{c}}(t)+8\right) d$ colors by (7), thus, $\psi$ is well-defined.

We now show that $Z$ and $\psi$ satisfy (pc1)-(pc3).
Recall that $X_{0}$ was chosen so that $X_{0} \subseteq X_{3}$ and $\bigcup_{y \in X_{0}} V_{y}$ intersects every member of $\mathcal{F}$. Therefore, (pc1) holds. Item (pc3) holds by Lemma 8 since $Z=\bigcup_{y \in \operatorname{LCA}\left(S, X_{2}\right)} V_{y}$, and $\mathcal{V}=$ $\left(S,\left(V_{y} \mid y \in V(S)\right)\right)$ is a natural tree decomposition of $G_{0}$.

It remains to prove (pc2). Consider a connected subgraph $H$ of $G_{0}$ such that $V(H) \cap Z \neq \emptyset$. If $V(H) \cap B \neq \emptyset$, then since every vertex of $B$ has a unique color, any vertex in $V(H) \cap B$ is a $\psi$-center of $V(H) \cap Z$, and so, a $\varphi \times \psi$-center of $V(H) \cap Z$. Thus, we assume that $V(H) \cap B=\emptyset$.

Since $V(H) \cap B=\emptyset$, it follows from Claim 16, that $V(H) \cap Z \subseteq \bigcup_{z \in V(Q)} V_{z}$ for some $Q \in$ $\mathcal{Q}\left(X_{1}\right)$.

Additionally, by Claim 17,

$$
\begin{array}{ll}
V(H) \cap Z \subseteq W_{x}-A_{x} & \text { if } x=r \\
V(H) \cap Z \subseteq W_{x}-\left(A_{x} \cup W_{\mathrm{p}(T, x)}\right) & \text { if } x \neq r
\end{array}
$$

Recall that $\left(L_{x, i} \mid i \in \mathbb{N}\right)$ is a layering of $\operatorname{torso}_{G}\left(W_{x}\right)-A_{x}$. Moreover, by definition of $\varphi$, for every $u \in V(H) \cap Z, \varphi(u)=i \bmod (p+1)$ where $i \in \mathbb{N}$ is such that $u \in L_{x, i}$.

Consider $u \in V(H) \cap Z$. Let $i \in \mathbb{N}$ be such that $u \in L_{x, i}$. If $u$ is a $(\varphi \times \psi)$-center in $V(H) \cap Z$, then we are done. Assume now that there exists $u^{\prime} \in V(H) \cap Z$ distinct from $u$ such that $\varphi(u)=\varphi\left(u^{\prime}\right)$ and $\psi(u)=\psi\left(u^{\prime}\right)$. Let $j \in \mathbb{N}$ be such that $u^{\prime} \in L_{x, j}$. Without loss of generality, assume that $i \leqslant j$. By the definition of $\psi, j \neq i$, and by the definition of $\varphi,|j-i|>p$. By Lemma 10, $V(H) \cap W_{x}$ induces a connected subgraph of $\operatorname{torso}_{G}\left(W_{x}\right)-A_{x}$. Since $\left(L_{x, k} \mid k \in \mathbb{N}\right)$ is a layering of $\operatorname{torso}_{G}\left(W_{x}\right)-A_{x}$, it follows that $V(H)$ intersects $L_{x, k}$ for every $k \in\{i, \ldots, j-1\}$. We deduce that $|\varphi(V(H))|>p$. Therefore, we obtain (pc2), which ends the proof.

abstract:
A vertex coloring $\varphi$ of a graph $G$ is $p$-centered if for every
connected subgraph $H$ of $G$, either $\varphi$ uses more than $p$ colors on
$H$, or there is a color that appears exactly once on $H$. We prove that for
every fixed positive integer $t$, every $K_t$-minor-free graph admits a
$p$-centered coloring using $\mathcal{O}(p^{t-1})$ colors.
